## Git Works:

Git is built on two core concepts:

| Concept | What It Means |
|---|---|
| **Cryptographic Hashing (SHA-1)** | Every commit gets a unique 40-character fingerprint. Even a tiny change in content produces a completely different hash — this is how Git guarantees data integrity. |
| **Snapshots** | Unlike some version control systems that store file-by-file differences, Git stores a full snapshot of your project at each commit. |

### Refs (References) — Git's "Pointers"

Think of refs as labeled bookmarks pointing to specific commits:

| Ref Type | Points To | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| **Branch** | The *latest* commit in a line of work | Moves forward automatically as you commit |
| **Tag** | One specific commit | Stays fixed — doesn't move unless you force it to |
| **HEAD** | Ideally, a branch or tag | Tells Git "where you currently are" |
| **Remote ref** | A branch on a remote repo (e.g., `origin/main`) | Tracks the state of the remote |

> **Detached HEAD** — Normally, HEAD points to a *branch* (like `master`), which in turn points to a commit. If HEAD points *directly* to a commit instead of a branch, you're in a **detached HEAD** state. Any new commits here aren't attached to a branch and can be lost once you switch away — unless you create a branch to save them.

**Analogy:** Imagine a branch as a sticky note that always moves to the newest page you write in a notebook (chapter). A tag is like a sticky note glued permanently to one specific page — it won't move even if you keep writing.

