## Real-World Scenarios — Why Branches & Tags Exist

Git provides **branches** and **tags** specifically to handle situations like these:

### Scenario 1: A product like VS Code
- Software like VS Code releases numbered **versions** (v1.85, v1.86, etc.)
- **Tags** are perfect here — each release gets a permanent marker (e.g., `v1.85.0`) so you can always go back to exactly that version.

### Scenario 2: A product like an HRMS (HR Management System) sold to customers
- Different customers may need **customer-specific changes** (custom fields, integrations, etc.)
- **Branches** work well here — you can maintain a separate branch per customer while still being able to merge in common updates from the main product.

