## Git Branch

- By default, when you start working in Git, you're on a branch — traditionally called `master` (or `main` in modern setups).
- A branch lets you develop features, fixes, or experiments **in isolation** without affecting the main codebase.
- 📖 Further reading: [Atlassian — Using Branches](https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/using-branches)

### Merging — Bringing Changes Together

To bring changes from one branch into another, you perform a **merge**:

```bash
git checkout <destination-branch>   # Step 1: Go to the branch you want to update
git merge <source-branch>           # Step 2: Pull in changes from another branch
```

**Example:** To bring changes from `feature-login` into `master`:
```bash
git checkout master
git merge feature-login
```

📖 Further reading: [Atlassian — Git Merge](https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/using-branches/git-merge)

### Types of Merges

| Merge Type | When It Happens | Result |
|---|---|---|
| **Fast-Forward** | Destination branch has no new commits since it diverged | Destination branch pointer simply moves forward — no new merge commit created |
| **Three-Way Merge** | Both branches have new, different commits since they diverged | Git creates a new **merge commit** combining both histories |

